1 Explain fail-fast and fail-safe iterators.
ANS :
	Fail-Fast Iterator:
		- Operates directly on the collection.
		- If the collection is modified structurally (add/remove elements) after the iterator is created, it throws ConcurrentModificationException.
		- Example collections: ArrayList, HashMap, HashSet.
		- Use case: Detects concurrent modification bugs early.

	Fail-Safe Iterator:
		- Operates on a clone or snapshot of the collection.
		- Can safely modify the collection while iterating.
		- Example collections: ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList.
		- Use case: Used in multi-threaded environments to avoid exceptions.

2 What is the Iterator interface?
ANS :
	- Definition: Provides a standard way to traverse any collection sequentially.
	- Package: java.util
	Key Methods:
	
	- boolean hasNext() – checks if more elements exist.
	- E next() – returns the next element.
	- void remove() – removes the current element (optional operation).
	
	Example:
	
	- List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(List.of("A", "B", "C"));
	- Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
	- while(it.hasNext()) {
	    System.out.println(it.next());
		} 
		
3 What is the ListIterator interface? 
ANS :
	- Extends Iterator and works only with List implementations.
	Key Features:
	- Can traverse both forward and backward.
	- Can modify elements using set() or add new elements using add().
	- Supports index-based iteration with nextIndex() and previousIndex().
	Key Methods:
	- boolean hasPrevious(), E previous() – backward traversal.
	- void set(E e) – replaces last element returned.
	- void add(E e) – inserts element at current position.

4 What are Comparable and Comparator interfaces? 
ANS :
	Comparable Interface:
	- Defines natural ordering of objects.
	- Package: java.lang
	- Method: int compareTo(T obj)
	- Only one way of comparison per class.
	- Comparator Interface:
	- Defines custom or multiple orderings for objects.
	- Package: java.util
	Methods:
	- int compare(T o1, T o2)
	- boolean equals(Object obj) (optional)

5 Difference between Comparable and Comparator.
ANS :
	- Purpose: Comparable defines natural ordering; Comparator defines custom or multiple orderings.
	- Package: Comparable is in java.lang; Comparator is in java.util.
	- Method: Comparable uses compareTo(T o); Comparator uses compare(T o1, T o2).
	- Implementation: Comparable is implemented by the class whose objects are compared; Comparator is implemented by a separate class or lambda.
	- Number of Orders: Comparable allows only one natural order; Comparator allows multiple custom orders.
	- Modification: Comparable requires modifying the class; Comparator does not require modifying the class.
	- Use Case: Comparable is used for default sorting; Comparator is used for flexible, external sorting criteria.